WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.480
Hi everyone, my name is Tyler Morgan-Wall, I'm the developer of Rayshader and the Rayverse,

00:00:11.480 --> 00:00:16.320
and in the next 15 minutes, I'm going to tell you how you can turn your 3D data visualizations

00:00:16.320 --> 00:00:20.080
into a theme park ride entirely in R.

00:00:20.080 --> 00:00:24.160
Now before we get started, I want you to think back to the very first theme park ride or

00:00:24.160 --> 00:00:26.080
rollercoaster you ever went on.

00:00:26.080 --> 00:00:32.540
I for one very clearly remember my first rollercoaster ride because I was 7 and it was a disaster.

00:00:32.540 --> 00:00:38.279
It was a bumpy, rough wooden coaster that bruised my ribs and rattled my spine, and

00:00:38.279 --> 00:00:42.439
every hill, turn, and bump is still ingrained in my mind.

00:00:42.439 --> 00:00:48.240
Now I don't have many memories from when I was 7, but that is one of them.

00:00:48.240 --> 00:00:54.080
Now I want you to try to think back to the first data visualization you ever made.

00:00:54.080 --> 00:01:02.020
It was probably something like this, this, or god forbid, this.

00:01:02.020 --> 00:01:06.120
But you probably don't remember the first data visualization you ever put together.

00:01:06.120 --> 00:01:11.139
And that's because we tend to remember things in our lives that elicit an emotional response.

00:01:11.139 --> 00:01:16.680
My first rollercoaster ride stuck with me because of the emotions it evoked, even if

00:01:16.680 --> 00:01:18.519
they were negative.

00:01:18.519 --> 00:01:22.480
Now you might be thinking, well, data visualizations aren't supposed to evoke emotion, they're

00:01:22.480 --> 00:01:25.519
supposed to be about informing the reader.

00:01:25.519 --> 00:01:28.839
And to that, I like to make an analogy to another type of institution that needs to

00:01:28.839 --> 00:01:34.680
balance fun and interesting with informative and educational, museums.

00:01:34.680 --> 00:01:39.879
I like to look at building a data visualization like a museum curating an exhibit.

00:01:39.879 --> 00:01:44.739
Museums can have a bunch of self-contained exhibits that are static, small in scope,

00:01:44.739 --> 00:01:49.040
and designed so that viewers can digest the information at their own pace, much like most

00:01:49.040 --> 00:01:50.959
data visualizations.

00:01:50.959 --> 00:01:56.559
But that doesn't mean museums can't also build a giant IMAX theater or include a virtual

00:01:56.559 --> 00:02:02.320
reality thrill ride, something that will evoke a feeling of excitement in patrons long after

00:02:02.320 --> 00:02:06.480
the information from the placards has faded from their memory.

00:02:06.480 --> 00:02:10.759
So these are two pictures from the Air and Space Museums here in D.C.

00:02:10.759 --> 00:02:14.440
They have exhibits that both inform and entertain.

00:02:14.440 --> 00:02:16.160
And this isn't just conjecture.

00:02:16.160 --> 00:02:20.479
Numerous studies have shown that the most vivid memories tend to be of emotional events,

00:02:20.479 --> 00:02:24.639
which are recalled with more clarity and detail than neutral events.

00:02:24.639 --> 00:02:30.160
So while not every exhibit should be a thrill ride, that doesn't mean none can be.

00:02:30.160 --> 00:02:34.399
I'm going to show you how you can make experiences out of your data visualizations.

00:02:34.399 --> 00:02:39.039
How you can turn a ggplot into a heart-pounding ride.

00:02:39.039 --> 00:02:43.800
Now it doesn't necessarily have to be a fast-moving roller coaster like this.

00:02:43.800 --> 00:02:47.960
Yours might be more It's a Small World than Space Mountain.

00:02:47.960 --> 00:02:51.199
I want you to have this tool in your skill set, and I'm going to show you how you don't

00:02:51.199 --> 00:02:58.759
need any fancy 3D modeling skills or Pixar-level animation skills to make fun 3D rides.

00:02:58.759 --> 00:03:01.600
So here's what you'll learn in the next 12 minutes.

00:03:01.600 --> 00:03:08.160
How to make a 3D roller coaster in R. But also why you might want to.

00:03:08.160 --> 00:03:12.360
But first, I'm going to go over some basic ways to make 3D plots in R that don't require

00:03:12.360 --> 00:03:17.160
any fancy skills, and I'll go over what makes a good 3D data viz.

00:03:17.160 --> 00:03:21.399
And finally, the most common feedback I get when I give a talk on 3D data visualization

00:03:21.399 --> 00:03:27.000
is, wow, I wish I could make something like that, but I don't work with any 3D data.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:31.759
So throughout this presentation, I'm going to give a bunch of examples of 3D data visualizations

00:03:31.759 --> 00:03:35.960
made from a variety of different data sets all in R that will hopefully give you some

00:03:35.960 --> 00:03:40.479
inspiration to try and make something of your own.

00:03:40.479 --> 00:03:45.240
Now there are a few packages out there for 3D data visualization, but I'm going to talk

00:03:45.240 --> 00:03:50.600
about the Ravers, the set of packages I developed that focuses on making high-quality 3D renders

00:03:50.600 --> 00:03:52.600
with realistic lighting.

00:03:52.600 --> 00:03:56.479
The main package I'll be using in this process is ray render, a package that enables you

00:03:56.479 --> 00:04:03.279
to make beautiful path trace 3D visualizations entirely in R. The ray shader package will

00:04:03.279 --> 00:04:08.399
be used to transform your data into 3D models using either geospatial data or the incredibly

00:04:08.399 --> 00:04:11.259
simple 3D ggplot interface.

00:04:11.259 --> 00:04:16.500
And finally, I wrote the ray rollercoaster package specifically for this talk.

00:04:16.500 --> 00:04:21.859
It automates the entire rollercoaster construction process down to two functions, one to interactively

00:04:21.859 --> 00:04:25.619
build your coaster and another to animate it.

00:04:25.619 --> 00:04:27.100
So let's cover the basics.

00:04:27.100 --> 00:04:30.500
What exactly goes into a 3D data visualization?

00:04:30.500 --> 00:04:34.579
First, what kind of data can be used in 3D plots?

00:04:34.579 --> 00:04:39.279
All you need for a 3D data is are data with at least three numeric components.

00:04:39.279 --> 00:04:44.160
Here we have European flight path data from the crowdsourced open sky network.

00:04:44.160 --> 00:04:49.600
Flight path data has latitude, longitude, and altitude, which intuitively correspond

00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:55.000
as to X, Y, and Z, and are here plotted as 3D paths.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:59.279
This is a fairly straightforward and intuitive use of 3D, but you can also choose to use

00:04:59.279 --> 00:05:02.399
3D aesthetics with 2D data.

00:05:02.399 --> 00:05:06.480
Much like you might choose a line chart over a bar chart purely for aesthetic reasons,

00:05:06.480 --> 00:05:10.559
you might also choose a 3D chart over its 2D counterpart because you can make it more

00:05:10.559 --> 00:05:13.500
interesting and visually appealing.

00:05:13.500 --> 00:05:18.040
This is a map of the submarine fiber optic cable network, and there's no actual 3D data

00:05:18.040 --> 00:05:20.920
present, just latitude and longitude data.

00:05:20.920 --> 00:05:25.160
The cables rise out of the earth where they start and fall back in where they land.

00:05:25.160 --> 00:05:30.079
You could easily plot this as simple 2D paths on a world map, but I think the floating cables,

00:05:30.079 --> 00:05:33.760
subtle shadows, and rotating globe really elevate what is otherwise a fairly simple

00:05:33.760 --> 00:05:38.200
data set into something more relatable and tangible on a human scale, like the earth

00:05:38.200 --> 00:05:41.200
is being wrapped in yarn.

00:05:41.200 --> 00:05:47.239
So many 2D plots have direct 3D equivalents, but just replacing points and lines with spheres

00:05:47.239 --> 00:05:50.019
and cylinders can lead to mixed results.

00:05:50.019 --> 00:05:54.279
Data floating in the void can be hard to interpret if we're just presented with a static image,

00:05:54.279 --> 00:05:58.079
as objects in the foreground can block those in the background, as we see here in this

00:05:58.079 --> 00:06:04.000
rendering of a morphine molecule generated with the ray molecule package.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:09.119
But you can solve this problem by animating the 3D data.

00:06:09.119 --> 00:06:13.600
The movement disambiguates the foreground from the background so that the reader can

00:06:13.600 --> 00:06:17.760
fully interpret the 3D model.

00:06:17.760 --> 00:06:22.880
Besides points and lines, the other main type of 3D data visualization is the 3D mesh, a

00:06:22.880 --> 00:06:25.380
continuous grid of data values.

00:06:25.380 --> 00:06:27.739
This is where the ray shader package comes in.

00:06:27.739 --> 00:06:32.739
It takes 2D grids of raster data and creates 3D models by transforming the flat matrix

00:06:32.739 --> 00:06:34.540
data into 3D.

00:06:34.540 --> 00:06:39.339
So this visualization of the underwater volcano in Tonga that erupted earlier this year was

00:06:39.339 --> 00:06:45.940
generated from a simple 2D matrix of bathymetry values taken from a sonar survey.

00:06:45.940 --> 00:06:50.820
Check out the code to see how straightforward this is, from R matrix to 3D model in just

00:06:50.820 --> 00:06:53.299
a few function calls.

00:06:53.540 --> 00:06:56.779
This is true of almost all of the visualizations you'll see in this talk.

00:06:56.779 --> 00:07:00.299
The rendering script is usually only a dozen or so lines of code.

00:07:00.299 --> 00:07:04.700
Most of the work is in cleaning the data as it always is.

00:07:04.700 --> 00:07:07.859
So when you're dealing with non-topographic data, the process is similar.

00:07:07.859 --> 00:07:12.140
You can convert the previously 2D data by extruding it into the third dimension.

00:07:12.140 --> 00:07:16.779
If you're having trouble conceptualizing what type of data can be used for a 3D mesh, one

00:07:16.779 --> 00:07:20.820
rule of thumb is that any type of data that can be mapped to the fill or color aesthetic

00:07:20.820 --> 00:07:24.500
in ggplot can also be mapped to 3D.

00:07:24.500 --> 00:07:29.500
Here we have a plot of infections in Jon Snow's famous cholera data set where the points are

00:07:29.500 --> 00:07:33.220
colored by the number of nearest neighbors for each infection.

00:07:33.220 --> 00:07:38.459
The process of converting ggplots to 3D is fully automated in RayShader's plot gg function.

00:07:38.459 --> 00:07:42.739
And if you want to learn more information, check out my RStudioConf 2020 talk on making

00:07:42.739 --> 00:07:46.299
3D ggplots with RayShader.

00:07:46.299 --> 00:07:50.940
So one reason you might consider using 3D instead of color is that encoding data to

00:07:50.940 --> 00:07:55.980
color requires the viewer to reference a color bar to understand the ordering of the data.

00:07:55.980 --> 00:08:00.079
As there's no intuitive reason why some colors correspond to lower values and some colors

00:08:00.079 --> 00:08:01.779
correspond to higher.

00:08:01.779 --> 00:08:06.339
Here I plotted the heights of buildings in Seattle, Washington by mapping the data to

00:08:06.339 --> 00:08:07.339
color.

00:08:07.339 --> 00:08:12.299
Height, on the other hand, intuitively allows you to judge which values are less than or

00:08:12.299 --> 00:08:14.000
greater than others.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:18.079
You can tell when a building here is about half the height of another without having

00:08:18.079 --> 00:08:20.200
to reference an external color bar.

00:08:20.200 --> 00:08:25.959
However, because 3D introduces ambiguity in the depth axis, you lose precision.

00:08:25.959 --> 00:08:30.600
Thus 3D data visualizations are great when the exact numeric values aren't important

00:08:30.600 --> 00:08:34.159
but comparing relative values and getting an overall sense of the distribution of data

00:08:34.159 --> 00:08:36.119
is.

00:08:36.119 --> 00:08:40.539
Using both 3D and color can give you the best of both worlds.

00:08:40.539 --> 00:08:44.179
Color to indicate precise numeric levels and height to give a more intuitive way to

00:08:44.179 --> 00:08:45.979
compare values.

00:08:45.979 --> 00:08:49.900
Here we have a visualization I made of the global population density using both color

00:08:49.900 --> 00:08:51.260
and height.

00:08:51.260 --> 00:08:55.479
The use of color allows the viewer to map data to direct population intervals while

00:08:55.479 --> 00:09:00.820
the use of height establishes order without needing to reference a legend.

00:09:00.820 --> 00:09:05.440
Now if you're the type of person like me that likes to obsess over the tiniest details of

00:09:05.440 --> 00:09:11.799
your data viz, good news, 3D brings an entirely new type of detail to obsess about, lighting.

00:09:11.799 --> 00:09:15.719
Move over adjusting ggplot margins.

00:09:15.719 --> 00:09:19.799
If you've ever talked to a photographer, you know the real secret to amazing photographs

00:09:19.799 --> 00:09:24.760
isn't necessarily having the best equipment but rather having adequate and well-designed

00:09:24.760 --> 00:09:26.320
lighting.

00:09:26.320 --> 00:09:31.239
If you only have a single light like we do here in this 3D historical map, this visualization

00:09:31.320 --> 00:09:36.239
is a bit spooky, like a swing light bulb in a haunted house.

00:09:36.239 --> 00:09:41.599
If we look at this visualization of the blooming California poppy fields, we see with multiple

00:09:41.599 --> 00:09:45.520
distant fill lights, we see the atmosphere has changed completely.

00:09:45.520 --> 00:09:48.359
Much less moody and much brighter.

00:09:48.359 --> 00:09:53.200
Even easier than all of that is using an HDR image file for environment-based lighting,

00:09:53.200 --> 00:09:57.760
which we see here in this visualization of Monterey Bay, California.

00:09:57.760 --> 00:10:01.799
It lights the scene with a real-world image, which results in natural, realistic lighting

00:10:01.799 --> 00:10:05.500
like your scene was in that environment.

00:10:05.500 --> 00:10:10.640
If your data changes over time, you can then also introduce animation to your data viz.

00:10:10.640 --> 00:10:15.719
Here I used a Microsoft connect to capture my movements and load them into R using the

00:10:15.719 --> 00:10:18.280
R mocap package.

00:10:18.280 --> 00:10:22.679
By extracting the individual time slices from the movement data and rendering each frame

00:10:22.679 --> 00:10:28.440
completely, I was able to combine all the frames into this animation using the AV package.

00:10:28.440 --> 00:10:33.640
So watch out, Pixar, R users are coming for you.

00:10:33.640 --> 00:10:39.479
You can even use this ability to bring old friends back from the dead.

00:10:39.479 --> 00:10:42.440
Thank you.

00:10:42.440 --> 00:10:44.440
Thank you.

00:10:44.440 --> 00:10:50.159
So here I've used R and RayRender to bring Microsoft Clippy back to life to help you

00:10:50.159 --> 00:10:53.400
debug your data analysis pipeline.

00:10:53.400 --> 00:10:59.559
Maybe an idea for Posit's next professional product?

00:10:59.559 --> 00:11:04.239
And for the creatively inclined, you can also produce stunning generative art in 3D using

00:11:04.239 --> 00:11:05.679
RayRender.

00:11:05.679 --> 00:11:10.200
Here I've simulated and plotted the trajectory of a particle in a strange attractor, a type

00:11:10.200 --> 00:11:13.380
of differential equation that displays chaotic motion.

00:11:13.380 --> 00:11:17.119
I've lit the scene with both a white and red light and changed the material of the object

00:11:17.119 --> 00:11:19.119
to give it a glossy sheen.

00:11:19.119 --> 00:11:22.760
We can also generate fractal trees using the ray bonsai package.

00:11:22.760 --> 00:11:27.559
This is a rewrite of Daniel Navarro's flame tree package to work in 3D and you can create

00:11:27.559 --> 00:11:32.760
all different types of trees, two or three lines of code, all generated in R with nothing

00:11:32.760 --> 00:11:34.960
but math.

00:11:34.960 --> 00:11:39.320
And finally, unlike in 2D where there's only one way to look at a visualization, in 3D

00:11:39.320 --> 00:11:44.080
you have an infinite number of camera angles, orientations and settings to choose from.

00:11:44.080 --> 00:11:48.140
It can be intimidating, especially if you've never worked in 3D before.

00:11:48.140 --> 00:11:53.460
But I've made it a little less daunting by including a fully interactive, real-time 3D

00:11:53.460 --> 00:11:58.539
to graphics device built into RayRender and working out of the box with no dependencies

00:11:58.539 --> 00:12:00.820
or no weird dependencies.

00:12:00.820 --> 00:12:04.979
You can fly around your scene with just your mouse and keyboard and find the best angle

00:12:04.979 --> 00:12:08.299
and print out your camera info for future use.

00:12:08.299 --> 00:12:11.760
This is all happening directly in your R session.

00:12:11.760 --> 00:12:16.460
You can even interactively save key frames and then generate an animation smoothly flying

00:12:16.500 --> 00:12:22.580
through your data visualization or as I'm about to show you, riding through it.

00:12:22.580 --> 00:12:27.059
Now that you know everything you need to know to make a 3D data viz in R, let's build a

00:12:27.059 --> 00:12:29.700
roller coaster.

00:12:29.700 --> 00:12:33.380
First we need to generate a 3D scene for our roller coaster to travel through.

00:12:33.380 --> 00:12:37.539
Now this could be any of the visualizations I've shown up to this point, but I'm going

00:12:37.539 --> 00:12:43.500
to use a 3D ggplot because RayShader's 3D ggplot interface is by far the easiest way

00:12:43.500 --> 00:12:55.940
to make a slick 3D data viz in R. This is one function called passing the ggplot object

00:12:55.940 --> 00:12:59.539
and voila, a fully formed 3D data viz.

00:12:59.539 --> 00:13:03.619
You might note that I've turned off RayShader's ray tracing because we're going to get a much

00:13:03.619 --> 00:13:08.460
higher quality version of ray tracing when we render the scene with RayRender.

00:13:08.460 --> 00:13:13.500
Now that we have our 3D scene set up, here's where the ray roller coaster package comes

00:13:13.500 --> 00:13:14.500
in.

00:13:14.500 --> 00:13:18.400
Here all we need to do is call the generate ray shader coaster function which extracts

00:13:18.400 --> 00:13:23.280
the ray shader scene for you and automates the entire roller coaster construction process.

00:13:23.280 --> 00:13:28.260
This function uses RayRender's built in interactive graphics device to let you fly around the

00:13:28.260 --> 00:13:33.659
scene and build a roller coaster directly in R. Here I've recorded a video of myself

00:13:33.659 --> 00:13:38.380
flying through the scene, pressing K at the key positions I want my roller coaster to

00:13:38.380 --> 00:13:39.940
travel through.

00:13:39.940 --> 00:13:45.340
When I'm done and close the window, it will generate a 3D model of a roller coaster that

00:13:45.340 --> 00:13:47.739
travels through those points.

00:13:47.739 --> 00:13:51.780
Now I've extracted the full 3D scene here with get ray render scene and used render

00:13:51.780 --> 00:13:57.419
scene to get an overhead isometric view of the ride, sort of like roller coaster tycoon

00:13:57.419 --> 00:14:00.419
but with less death and destruction.

00:14:00.419 --> 00:14:04.820
Now that we're happy with our roller coaster, all that's left is simply calling animate

00:14:04.820 --> 00:14:12.140
roller coaster with a movie file name and we get our full first person animated roller

00:14:12.140 --> 00:14:25.020
coaster ride through our data set entirely in R. Ta-da!

00:14:25.059 --> 00:14:28.900
So we're all done creating our roller coaster.

00:14:28.900 --> 00:14:30.700
Or are we?

00:14:30.700 --> 00:14:35.859
You see, while this is cool, you might note that it's more ride than data viz.

00:14:35.859 --> 00:14:40.700
You can't look around because the field of view here is fixed at 120 degrees and the

00:14:40.700 --> 00:14:43.460
camera view is stuck along the track.

00:14:43.460 --> 00:14:49.099
If instead we set the field of view to 360 degrees, we can render the entire scene at

00:14:49.099 --> 00:14:53.340
every frame which gives us something that looks like this.

00:14:53.340 --> 00:14:58.460
So this is rendering a complete sphere surrounding the camera at every frame so that we can see

00:14:58.460 --> 00:15:00.340
every angle at once.

00:15:00.340 --> 00:15:03.260
This allows the viewer to choose where to look.

00:15:03.260 --> 00:15:09.179
Now this animation looks rather funky and warped, but we aren't going to use the video

00:15:09.179 --> 00:15:15.380
in this form because you can do something very special with 360 degree videos.

00:15:15.380 --> 00:15:20.659
By injecting a little metadata to the MP4 file and uploading to YouTube, you can turn

00:15:20.659 --> 00:15:26.659
this video into a virtual reality 3D roller coaster and put yourself directly inside your

00:15:26.659 --> 00:15:35.340
data viz.

00:15:35.340 --> 00:15:39.900
Now the viewer can look and direct their attention to wherever they want as they fly along the

00:15:39.900 --> 00:15:41.299
track.

00:15:41.299 --> 00:15:45.299
Because you control where you look, it truly feels like you're riding a thrill ride with

00:15:45.299 --> 00:15:51.179
exciting vertigo-inducing drops and dizzying turns that truly leaves an impression.

00:15:51.179 --> 00:15:53.619
You don't need any fancy VR gear to experience this.

00:15:53.619 --> 00:15:59.299
I made this video with just my phone and a $20 VR head mount and it only took a dozen

00:15:59.299 --> 00:16:05.219
or so lines of code to put together thanks to the power of R and the Ravers.

00:16:05.219 --> 00:16:09.539
So in summary, 3D plotting is an awesome tool you should consider trying out and there's

00:16:09.539 --> 00:16:14.380
no better ecosystem out there for 3D data viz than R.

00:16:14.460 --> 00:16:17.940
Thanks to RayRender's interactive renderer and the Ray roller coaster package, building

00:16:17.940 --> 00:16:21.940
an impressive thrill ride through your 3D world is dead simple and only takes a few

00:16:21.940 --> 00:16:23.500
lines of code.

00:16:23.500 --> 00:16:27.880
And finally, consider combining the tools of virtual reality with 3D data viz to immerse

00:16:27.880 --> 00:16:30.659
your viewers on rides or tours throughout your data.

00:16:30.659 --> 00:16:34.340
By actually putting your viewers in the data visualization, you can form longer lasting

00:16:34.340 --> 00:16:39.500
connections to your work by evoking emotion and allowing the user to experience your visualization

00:16:39.500 --> 00:16:42.460
in a more up close and personal way.

00:16:42.460 --> 00:16:44.539
Thank you so much for your time and enjoy the ride.

